The '''tornado outbreak of April 27–30, 2014''' was a relatively widespread, damaging and deadly [[tornado outbreak]] that struck the [[Central United States|central]] and [[southern United States]] in late April 2014. The storm complex responsible for the outbreak produced multiple long-track [[tornado]]es – seven were deadly, causing 35 fatalities.<ref name="AP">[http://www.cbc.ca/news/world/u-s-tornadoes-kill-35-over-2-days-1.2625256 U.S. tornadoes kill 35 over 2 days], [[CBC News]] (via the [[Associated Press]]), April 29, 2014.</ref> One additional death occurred in [[Florida]], due to severe flooding associated with this system.<ref>{{cite web|title=Widespread flooding turns deadly in Florida|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/devastating-flooding-turns-deadly-in-fla/|publisher=CBS News|accessdate=30 April 2014}}</ref>

<!--please don't list almost every state. Better to describe the range than have people add own states haphazardly -->This event was the first major tornado outbreak to hit the United States in 2014; it covered a large swath  from [[Nebraska]] to [[Louisiana]], [[Illinois]] to [[Florida]], and [[Oklahoma]] to [[North Carolina]].<!--please don't list almost every state. Better to describe the range than have people add own states haphazardly --> This system affected millions in the [[Northeastern United States]] on April 30,<ref name="AP"/> causing significant, damaging floods in [[Maryland]]<ref name="CSX">[https://www.baltimorebrew.com/2014/04/30/railroad-retaining-wall-collapses-in-charles-village/Railroad retaining wall collapses in Charles Village]{{dead link|date=October 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, ''[[Baltimore Brew]]'', April 30, 2014.</ref> and flash flood advisories as far north as [[New Jersey]], [[Pennsylvania]], and [[New York City|NYC]]'s [[New York metropolitan area|metropolitan area]] and suburbs.<ref>[http://www.accuweather.com/en/weather-news/dangerous-storms-i-95-ohio-wed/26285360 Dangerous Flash Flooding, Storms Threaten I-95 Wednesday Evening], [[AccuWeather]], April 30, 2014.</ref>

==Meteorological synopsis==
A strong mid-level [[Shortwave (meteorology)|shortwave]] [[Trough (meteorology)|trough]] developed into a closed [[low-pressure area]] as the system occluded over the central [[High Plains (United States)|High Plains]] on April 27, 2014. An associated surface cyclone reached peak intensity while a trailing cold front moved eastward across eastern Kansas, eastern Oklahoma and northern Texas. There were two areas where severe weather was expected, morning pre-frontal convection from Kansas and Oklahoma into Missouri and Iowa and warm sector [[supercell]] development across southeast Oklahoma and northeast Texas into Arkansas. The [[Storm Prediction Center]] indicated this system for 6 days in advance on its 4–8 day outlook.<ref>{{cite web|title=Apr 27, 2014 2000 UTC Day 1 Convective Outlook
|url=http://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/outlook/archive/2014/day1otlk_20140427_2000.html|work=Storm Prediction Center|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|date=April 27, 2014|accessdate=May 1, 2014}}</ref>

==Notable tornadoes==
{{Main|List of tornadoes in the tornado outbreak of April 27–30, 2014}}
{{April 27–30, 2014 tornado outbreak map}}
A total of 84&nbsp;tornadoes over a period of four days were confirmed. Collectively, they resulted in 35&nbsp;fatalities and over 300&nbsp;injuries.<ref name="AP"/>

