===Quapaw, Oklahoma–Baxter Springs, Kansas===
[[File:Quapaw, Oklahoma April 27, 2014 tornado damage.jpg|thumb|A home destroyed by the tornado in [[Quapaw, Oklahoma]]]]
The first significant tornado of the outbreak touched down over an open field at 5:29&nbsp;p.m. CDT (2229&nbsp;UTC) on April 27 to the southwest of [[Quapaw, Oklahoma]] and caused EF0 damage to a ranch.<ref name="NWSTulsa">{{cite web|work=National Weather Service office in Tulsa, Oklahoma|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|date=April 30, 2014|accessdate=May 3, 2014|title=Event Summary – 27 April 2014 Quapaw and Octavia Tornado Event|url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov//tsa/?n=weather-event_2014april27}}</ref> It caused minor damage to homes and downed trees as it neared [[U.S. Highway 69A (Oklahoma)|U.S. Highway 69A]]. Shortly thereafter, it struck the town of Quapaw at high-end EF2 strength and caused extensive damage. The local fire station was largely destroyed, and some industrial buildings sustained heavy damage. Homes in town were shifted off of their foundations or sustained loss of roofs and walls. Two people seeking shelter from the tornado in their car were struck by debris from the building they were next to; one of the occupants was killed while the other was injured. A total of 12&nbsp;people were injured in the town, 7&nbsp;of whom required hospitalization.<ref name="NWSTulsa"/> A total of 50&nbsp;structures were damaged or destroyed in Quapaw.<ref>{{cite web|author=Bryan Painter|publisher=News OK|date=April 30, 2014|accessdate=May 4, 2014|title=Quapaw tornado update|url=http://newsok.com/quapaw-tornado-update/article/4744580}}</ref> The storm continued northeast and crossed the Oklahoma–Kansas state line, causing EF1-strength damage to outbuildings and downing trees and power poles. It soon moved directly through the town of Baxter Springs at high-end EF2 strength, where many homes and businesses lost their roofs, several of which had their exterior walls collapse. 90 homes and 11 business were destroyed, and an additional seven businesses and 85 homes suffered damage in Baxter Springs.<ref>http://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=506202</ref> A total of 34&nbsp;people were injured in town, 9&nbsp;of whom were hospitalized.<ref name="KMBC">{{cite web|author=Peggy Breit|publisher=KMBC-TV|date=April 28, 2014|accessdate=May 4, 2014|title=34 people injured in Baxter Springs, Kansas tornado|url=http://www.kmbc.com/news/25-people-injured-in-baxter-springs-kansas-tornado/25690778}}</ref> The tornado continued northeast and eventually dissipated {{convert|2.5|mi|km|}} from the town at 5:42&nbsp;p.m. CDT (2242&nbsp;UTC).<ref name="NWSSpringfield">{{cite web|work=National Weather Service office in Springfield, Missouri|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|date=April 28, 2014|accessdate=May 3, 2014|title=April 27th, 2014 Baxter Springs Kansas Tornado |url=http://www.crh.noaa.gov/sgf/scripts/localdata.php?loc=appevents&data=2014/2014apr27/user2.htm}}</ref> Overall, the tornado remained on the ground for 13&nbsp;minutes along a {{convert|11.25|mi|km|}} path, causing 1&nbsp;death and 37 injuries.<ref name="NWSTulsa"/><ref name="NWSSpringfield"/>

This particular tornado was unusual in that no [[tornado warning]] was issued for Quapaw before it struck the town. Meteorologists at the National Weather Service later stated that radar signatures showed no signs of a tornado until it was already over the town and by the time the warning was issued, it had moved into Kansas.<ref name="TulsaWorld">{{cite web|author=Michael Dekker|publisher=Tulsa World|date=April 28, 2014|accessdate=May 4, 2014|title= Official: Tornado developed rapidly over Quapaw with no time to issue warning |url=http://www.tulsaworld.com/news/state/official-tornado-developed-rapidly-over-quapaw-with-no-time-to/article_ceaf5c88-cf2e-11e3-8a10-0017a43b2370.html}}</ref> The warning came only minutes before the tornado struck Baxter Springs, catching residents off-guard and forcing them to scramble for shelter.<ref name="KMBC"/>

===Mayflower–Vilonia, Arkansas===
[[File:April 27, 2014 Vilonia tornado aerial damage.jpg|thumb|An aerial view of the Parkwood Meadows subdivision in Vilonia, depicting several homes completely leveled and swept clean off their foundations. All of these homes lacked anchor bolts and their walls were not properly secured.<ref name="NWSLittleRock"/>]]
At 7:06&nbsp;p.m. on April&nbsp;27 (0006&nbsp;UTC on April&nbsp;28), a weak tornado touched down in extreme western [[Pulaski County, Arkansas]], roughly {{convert|6|mi|km|}} east of [[Paron, Arkansas|Paron]], and tracked north-northeast. Within a minute, the tornado dramatically intensified and struck a small residential area at EF3 intensity. There, two homes were destroyed and another was severely damaged. One of the homes was built with bolts along the foundation perimeter and was reduced to a bare slab, normally indicative of EF5 strength; however, it was found that the anchor bolts were not secured with nuts and washers, and nearby vehicles were not moved, which indicated a lesser intensity. Three people were killed in that area. The storm weakened as it turned more northeasterly and moved through a forested area. Damage to trees and homes in this area was rated EF1. At 7:14&nbsp;p.m. (0014&nbsp;UTC), it struck [[Northpoint, Arkansas|Northpoint]] as an EF2, causing severe damage to several homes. Roofs were removed entirely from homes, though the walls on these structures remained mostly intact. After briefly crossing [[Lake Maumelle]], the tornado caused significant tree damage between [[Roland, Arkansas|Roland]] and [[Natural Steps, Arkansas|Natural Steps]] with some trees being stripped of their foliage and debarked. Moving through an unpopulated area, the tornado intensified before crossing the [[Arkansas River]] and entering [[Faulkner County, Arkansas|Faulkner County]] around 7:26&nbsp;p.m. (0026&nbsp;UTC).<ref name="LittleRockSurvey">{{cite web|work=National Weather Service Office in Little Rock, Arkansas|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|date=May 1, 2014|accessdate=May 2, 2014|title=April 27, 2014 Arkansas tornado surveys|url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov/images/lzk/gis/tor042714a.kml|format=.KML}}</ref>

The tornado entered Faulkner County and immediately struck the River Plantation subdivision at the southwest edge of [[Mayflower, Arkansas|Mayflower]]. Here, EF4 damage took place  with large, two-story homes being leveled with only piles of debris left on their foundations. On the northeast side of the subdivision, one person was killed after debris struck the door of her [[storm shelter]] and opened it, exposing her to the tornado. The storm shelter's door was found to have been of sub-standard construction. Near where this fatality took place, large concrete road barriers were blown over and moved, and calculations revealed that this was also likely indicative of EF4 intensity.<ref name="LittleRockSurvey"/><ref name="American Meteorological Society">{{cite web |url=https://ams.confex.com/ams/27SLS/webprogram/Paper254346.html |title= Damage Survey of the Mayflower-Vilonia, Arkansas Tornado |last1=Marshall |first1=Timothy |date=November 6, 2014 |website=ams.confex.com |publisher=American Meteorological Society |accessdate=December 11, 2014}}</ref> Just outside the subdivision, a power substation sustained major damage. Continuing northeast, the storm tore across the south edge of Mayflower and crossed [[Arkansas Highway 365]] and [[Interstate 40]], tossing semi-trucks, cars, and road equipment from the highway. A business district in this area experienced mainly EF3 damage, with [[Semi-trailer truck|18-wheelers]] tossed, industrial buildings damaged or destroyed, and some nearby homes heavily damaged. A [[recreational vehicle]] dealership on the other side of the highway was completely destroyed at EF4 intensity (though meteorologist/civil engineer Tim Marshall applied an EF3 rating at this location due to structural flaws), along with most of the RVs; three of which were found wrapped around a nearby billboard. A vehicle repair shop, millwork company, construction company, and church in southern Mayflower were also destroyed, and a home improvement store was badly damaged.<ref name="ncdc.noaa.gov">http://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=504760</ref> In addition to the fatality in the storm shelter, two other people were killed in Mayflower.<ref name="ArkansasDeaths"/> The tornado then crossed [[Lake Conway]], downing numerous trees and causing a mixture of EF2 and EF3 damage to homes along the lakeshore. Some block-foundation frame homes along with multiple mobile homes were swept into the lake by the tornado. The Arkansas Game and Fish Commission lost a clubhouse, shop, horse barn, residence, metal carports, shower house, and several dog kennels in this area, and eventually removed 627 tons of tornado debris from the lake.<ref name="ncdc.noaa.gov"/> The tornado then caused mainly EF2 damage as it struck areas in and around [[Saltillo, Arkansas|Saltillo]]. Numerous homes, mobile homes, sheds, barns, trees, and a church were damaged or destroyed in the Saltillo area. Two homes near Saltillo had only interior walls left standing, with the damage to those homes rated EF3.<ref name="LittleRockSurvey"/>

[[File:Volume renderer view of tornado in Vilonia, AR.png|thumb|[[Weather radar]] [[reflectivity]] data in 3D of the [[supercell]] that produced the Vilonia tornado]]

Further northeast, the tornado began to re-intensify dramatically as it approached the [[U.S. Route 64 in Arkansas|Vilonia Bypass (U.S. Route 64)]], reaching EF4 strength for a second time. Just southwest of the bypass, some poorly-anchored homes were obliterated and swept from their foundations, and cars were tossed hundreds of yards away. Another frame home was left with only interior walls standing, and two mobile homes were obliterated with the frames thrown up to two streets away. Two children were killed in these homes.

Shortly before 7:50&nbsp;p.m. (0050&nbsp;UTC), the tornado moved into the town of [[Vilonia, Arkansas|Vilonia]] as a high-end EF4,<ref name="LittleRockSurvey"/> a town which was struck by [[2011 Super Outbreak#Vilonia, Arkansas|an EF2 tornado]] that killed four people on April&nbsp;25, 2011, three years and two days prior.<ref>{{cite web |author=Alexander Smith |publisher=NBC News |date=April 28, 2014 |accessdate=May 2, 2014 |title=Tornado Hits Vilonia, Arkansas, for 2nd Time in Just Three Years |url=http://www.nbcnews.com/storyline/deadly-tornado-outbreak/tornado-hits-vilonia-arkansas-2nd-time-just-three-years-n91176 |archivedate=May 2, 2014 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6PGraWwwG?url=http://www.nbcnews.com/storyline/deadly-tornado-outbreak/tornado-hits-vilonia-arkansas-2nd-time-just-three-years-n91176 |deadurl=no |df=mdy }}</ref> The EF4 Tornado first struck the recently built [[Vilonia School District|Vilonia Middle School]], destroying the top floor and causing most walls to collapse.<ref name="LittleRockSurvey"/> With winds estimated as high as {{convert|190|mph|km/h|abbr=on}} and the circulation spanning .75 miles,<ref name="vilonia"/> the tornado moved through the town center. Numerous homes and businesses were destroyed with only piles of debris or bare slabs left behind, and vehicles were thrown hundreds of yards and mangled beyond recognition, some of which were crushed into small balls or stripped down to their frames. Trees in town were completely debarked and denuded, low-lying shrubs were completely stripped and debarked, and extensive wind-rowing of debris occurred.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://darkroom.baltimoresun.com/2014/04/aerial-assessment-of-southern-states-tornado-damage/#1 |title=Aerial assessment of southern states tornado damage |last1=Gordon |first1=Kalani |date=April 30, 2013 |website=The Dark Room |publisher=The Baltimore Sun |access-date=March 4, 2014}}</ref> An aerial flyover revealed an extensive swath of ground scouring through the town.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://thecabin.net/latest-news/2014-04-28/video-aerial-footage-mayflower-violnia-tornado#.VQMjzY7F-oy |title=Video: Aerial footage of Mayflower, Vilonia tornado |date=April 28, 2014 |website=thecabin.net |publisher=The Log Cabin Democrat |access-date=March 13, 2015}}</ref> A dollar store, a strip mall, two auto repair shops, the old city hall, a gas station, a church life center, a real estate office, an investment firm, an auto parts store, and a fried fish restaurant were all completely destroyed in downtown Vilonia. The crumpled remains of a 29,998-pound metal fertilizer tank was found behind the destroyed strip mall, nearly 3/4 of a mile away from where it originated.<ref name="American Meteorological Society"/><ref name="ncdc.noaa.gov"/> Nine people were killed in the town.<ref name="LittleRockSurvey"/><ref name="ArkansasDeaths"/> As it moved out of downtown Vilonia, it tore directly through the Parkwood Meadows subdivision at the northeast side of town. Entire rows of homes were reduced to bare slabs at this location, though it was revealed that the homes were nailed rather than bolted to their foundations, preventing a rating higher than EF4.<ref name="LittleRockSurvey"/>

Continuing past Vilonia, the tornado weakened to EF3 strength as it passed just south of Williams Lake. A large metal arena building and a mobile home were destroyed in that area, with a few other structures sustaining EF1 damage nearby. Shortly after 8:00&nbsp;p.m. (0100&nbsp;UTC) the storm moved through densely forested areas and into [[White County, Arkansas|White County]], just west of [[El Paso, Arkansas|El Paso]]. The tornado briefly regained EF2 status and destroyed two manufactured homes.<ref name="LittleRockSurvey"/> One person was killed in one of the manufactured homes at this location.<ref name="ArkansasDeaths">{{cite web |publisher=Arkansas Matters |date=April 29, 2014 |accessdate=May 2, 2014 |title=Remembering the Arkansas Tornado Victims |url=http://www.arkansasmatters.com/story/d/story/remembering-the-arkansas-tornado-victims/22658/7tw_zTLrSU60eqHbqeIBbQ |archivedate=May 2, 2014 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6PGspSgwf?url=http://www.arkansasmatters.com/story/d/story/remembering-the-arkansas-tornado-victims/22658/7tw_zTLrSU60eqHbqeIBbQ |deadurl=no |df=mdy }}</ref> It soon dissipated at 8:06&nbsp;p.m. (0106&nbsp;UTC) roughly {{convert|1|mi|km|}} north-northeast of El Paso near a forested area.<ref name="LittleRockSurvey"/>

Overall, the tornado remained on the ground for an hour, from 7:06&nbsp;p.m. to 8:06&nbsp;p.m. (0006&nbsp;– 0106&nbsp;UTC), and traveled along a {{convert|41.3|mi|km|}} path. Sixteen people lost their lives due to the tornado,<ref name="vilonia">{{cite web|title=NWS Damage Survey for 04/27/14 Tornado Event|url=https://nwschat.weather.gov/p.php?pid=201404290123-KLZK-NOUS44-PNSLZK|work=National Weather Service, Little Rock, Arkansas|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|date=April 28, 2014|accessdate=April 28, 2014}}</ref> making it the deadliest in Arkansas since an F4 killed 35 on [[May 1968 tornado outbreak|May&nbsp;15, 1968]]. One hundred and ninety-three others were injured.<ref>{{cite web|title=Storm Events Database – Event Details|url=http://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=504758|publisher=National Climatic Data Center|accessdate=20 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Storm Events Database – Event Details|url=http://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=504760|publisher=National Climatic Data Center|accessdate=20 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Storm Events Database – Event Details|url=http://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=504762|publisher=National Climatic Data Center|accessdate=20 October 2014}}</ref> It was also the first EF4 tornado of 2014 in the United States as well as the first EF4 in Arkansas since [[List of tornadoes in the tornado outbreak sequence of May 21–26, 2011#May 24 event|May&nbsp;25, 2011]]. The final rating of this tornado was a source of controversy, and the National Weather Service office in Little Rock noted that if this tornado occurred prior to the change to the [[Enhanced Fujita Scale]] in 2007, it likely would have been rated as an F5 due to numerous homes being swept clean from their foundations. However, it was revealed that almost every home in Vilonia lacked anchor bolts and were anchored with cut nails instead. The new scale accounts for homes that use cut nails instead of anchor bolts, which do not effectively provide resistance against violent tornadoes. The final decision on an EF4 rating was based on this as well. However, meteorologist/civil engineer [[Timothy P. Marshall]] noted in his survey of the damage that the rating assigned was "lower bound", and despite the presence of construction flaws, this doesn't rule out "the possibility that EF5 winds could have occurred."<ref name="NWSLittleRock"/><ref name="American Meteorological Society"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.arktimes.com/ArkansasBlog/archives/2014/05/05/meteorologist-defends-ef4-rating-on-vilonia-tornado |title=Meteorologist defends EF4 rating on Vilonia tornado |last1=Brantley |first1=Max |date=May 5, 2014 |website=Arkansas Times |publisher=Arkansas Times |access-date=March 4, 2015}}</ref> Further inspection from surveyors revealed that one home that was swept away along E Wicker St. was indeed properly bolted to its foundation. However, an inspection of the context surrounding the house revealed that small trees in a ditch near the home were still standing, and that the residence had possibly been pummeled by heavy debris from downtown Vilonia, exacerbating the level of destruction. Surveyors decided against an upgrade to EF5 as a result.<ref name="NWSLittleRock"/>

===Louisville, Mississippi===
[[File:Louisville2014Tornado.JPG|thumb|left|EF4 damage in Louisville]]
This violent and long-tracked wedge tornado tracked across northern Mississippi and through the town of [[Louisville, Mississippi|Louisville]] on the evening of the 28th, killing ten people, injuring over eighty and leaving major damage in its wake. The tornado touched down in [[Leake County, Mississippi|Leake County]], initially snapping numerous trees at EF1 intensity as it moved through heavily forested areas.<ref name="Louisville EF-4 Tornado">{{cite web |url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov/jan/?n=2014_04_27_28_29_winston_tor |title=Louisville EF-4 Tornado |date=May 3, 2014 |website=NWS Jackson, Mississippi |publisher=NOAA |accessdate=May 4, 2014}}</ref> The tornado proceeded to reach EF2 intensity as it completely destroyed a mobile home and a metal building. Three cars were tossed nearby, and a frame home lost most of its roof, sustaining EF1 damage. Maintaining EF2 intensity, the tornado crossed into [[Winston County, Mississippi|Winston County]] at the [[Attala County, Mississippi|Attala]]/[[Neshoba County, Mississippi|Neshoba County]] border. Numerous trees were snapped and a house sustained roof damage at that location. The tornado then weakened momentarily, causing only EF1-strength tree damage as it moved through dense forest. Continuing northeast, the tornado reintensified dramatically and reached EF3 strength as it heavily damaged or destroyed several homes and metal chicken houses.<ref name="Louisville EF-4 Tornado"/> Some of the homes sustained collapse of their exterior walls. Slightly further along the path, a large area of trees along Hartness Rd sustained extreme denuding and debarking, with only stubs of the largest branches remaining. The severity and consistency of the debarking/denuding was severe enough that surveyors applied an EF4 rating at that location.<ref name="Louisville EF-4 Tornado"/> Numerous chicken houses were destroyed at EF3 intensity nearby.<ref name="Louisville EF-4 Tornado"/>

Slight weakening occurred beyond this point, with consistent EF2 damage occurring: a house had its roof torn off, a mobile home was completely destroyed, and numerous trees were snapped. The tornado then regained low-end EF4 intensity, where a large complex of metal chicken houses was completely obliterated with little trace of them left.<ref name="Louisville EF-4 Tornado"/> A nearby cell phone tower was toppled, and several homes at the edge of the path sustained roof damage. The tornado maintained EF4 strength as it moved northwest of [[Noxapater, Mississippi|Noxapater]], sweeping away a brick building and a brick home, obliterating a mobile home, and debarking numerous trees. The tornado then weakened slightly, snapping numerous trees and power poles and destroying chicken houses at EF3 intensity.<ref name="Louisville EF-4 Tornado"/> After that, the tornado weakened further, but maintained EF2 intensity as it made a dramatic turn to the north, roughly following and eventually crossing [[Mississippi Highway 15|Highway 15]]. Many trees and power poles were snapped, homes had their roofs torn off, and many mobile homes were completely destroyed in this area. One mobile home frame was found wrapped around a tree in this area.<ref name="Louisville EF-4 Tornado"/>

[[File:LouisvilleEF42014.JPG|thumb|Extreme tree damage in rural Winston County.]]
The tornado re-intensified as it continued sharply northeastward into the south side of Louisville at EF3 strength, destroying numerous homes in residential areas. The tornado then re-attained EF4 strength as it completely destroyed three large factories in an industrial area of town, including a [[Georgia-Pacific]] plywood plant.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.msnewsnow.com/story/25406089/the-storm-aftermath-in-winston-county |title=Body of missing Winston County 8-year-old found |last1=Conaway |first1=Brad |date=May 1, 2014 |website=msnewsnow.com |publisher=WLBT |accessdate=May 8, 2014}}</ref> The tornado maintained its strength as it devastated nearby subdivisions and an apartment complex, with some homes and one of the apartment buildings reduced to bare slabs.<ref name="Louisville EF-4 Tornado"/> Past this point, additional homes were destroyed at EF3 intensity, with debarking and denuding of trees noted. The tornado then passed through a wooded area and across the east edge of town, striking the Winston County Medical Center in the process. The building sustained EF3 damage, with numerous cars flipped and tossed in the parking lot. A daycare center and an automobile showroom were completely leveled across the street from the medical center, both of which were housed in manufactured structures.<ref name="Louisville EF-4 Tornado"/> The owner of the daycare center died while shielding a 4-year-old child from the tornado as it struck.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/national/daycare-worker-dies-protecting-girl-4-tornado-article-1.1776152 |title=Daycare worker dies protecting girl, 4, in Mississippi tornado |last1=Hensley |first1=Nicole |date=May 1, 2014 |website=NYDailyNews.com |publisher=NY Daily News |accessdate=May 8, 2014}}</ref> The tornado made another sharp turn and began moving due-north through residential areas on northeast side of town. Numerous homes sustained EF3 to EF4-strength damage in this area, including one that was reduced to a bare foundation slab. Continuing north of town, the tornado caused EF2 and EF3-strength damage to homes, trees, and power poles before dissipating in a wooded area near [[Mississippi Highway 25|Highway 25]]. Overall, ten people were killed by this tornado, and many others were injured.<ref name="Louisville EF-4 Tornado"/> Some victims were found hundreds of yards from their homes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sunherald.com/2014/05/01/5540362/body-of-louisville-boy-missing.html |title=Body of Louisville boy missing from tornado found |last1=Amy |first1=Jeff |date=May 1, 2013 |website=Sun Herald.com |publisher=The Sun Herald |accessdate=May 4, 2014 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140504103656/http://www.sunherald.com/2014/05/01/5540362/body-of-louisville-boy-missing.html |archivedate=May 4, 2014 |df= }}</ref> A wooden door from Louisville was found {{convert|30|mi|km|}} away at the [[Mississippi State University]] campus.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.clarionledger.com/story/news/local/2014/04/28/least-dead-miss-tornadoes-guard-deployed-tupelo-winston-co/8444897/ |title=At least 6 dead in Miss. tornadoes; Guard deployed to Tupelo, Winston Co. |last1=Chandler |first1=Clay |date=April 28, 2014 |website=clarionledger.com |publisher=The Clarion Ledger |accessdate=May 4, 2014}}</ref>

===Lincoln–Moore County, Tennessee===
[[File:April 28, 2014 Lincoln County, Tennessee EF3 radar image.png|thumb|Base Reflectivity radar image of the supercell thunderstorm that spawned the EF3 tornado at 8:19&nbsp;p.m. CDT (0119&nbsp;UTC).]]
At 8:09&nbsp;p.m. CDT on April&nbsp;28 (0109&nbsp;UTC on April&nbsp;29), a tornado touched down just north of the Alabama–Tennessee state line roughly {{convert|4|mi|km|}} southeast of [[Belleview, Tennessee]].<ref name="LincolnEF3Survey">{{cite web|work=National Weather Service office in Huntsville, Alabama|date=May 3, 2014|accessdate=May 5, 2014|title=Lincoln Road to Champ (Lincoln County, TN/Moore County, TN) Tornado Survey|url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov/images/hun/stormsurveys/2014-04-28/radar/linc_moore/kmz_files/storm_dat/doc.kmz|format=.KMZ}}</ref> Initially, only trees were downed as the storm moved northeast; however, it soon began intensifying as it approached residential areas.<ref name="NWSHuntsvilleLincoln">{{cite web|work=National Weather Service office in Huntsville, Tennessee|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|date=May 3, 2014|accessdate=May 5, 2014|title=NWS Huntsville Storm Surveys From April 28–29, 2014 Tornadoes: Lincoln Road to the Champ Community: [EF-3]|url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov/hun/?n=hunsur_2014-04-28#fortpayne}}</ref> It reached EF3 strength as it impacted a small community {{convert|5|mi|km|}} east-southeast of [[Flintville, Tennessee|Flintville]]. Three homes were destroyed with only their interior walls left standing. A double-wide mobile home was obliterated here as well, with its undercarriage being thrown {{convert|125|yd|m|}} away. The two occupants of this home were killed.<ref name="LincolnEF3Survey"/> Continuing northeast, a poorly-anchored home was almost completely leveled, with the debris being partially pushed off the foundation.<ref name="NWSHuntsvilleLincoln"/> Winds at this point were estimated to have peaked at {{convert|160|mph|km/h|abbr=on}}, ranking the tornado as a high-end EF3.<ref name="NWSHuntsville">{{cite web|work=National Weather Service office in Huntsville, Alabama|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|date=May 5, 2014|accessdate=May 5, 2014|title=Severe Weather Event April 28th–29th, 2014|url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov/hun/?n=main_4282014}}</ref> The tornado then struck the South Lincoln Elementary school around 8:14&nbsp;p.m. CDT (0114&nbsp;UTC),<ref name="NWSHuntsvilleLincoln"/> destroying a large portion of its roof, and caused EF2 damage to two nearby homes.<ref name="LincolnEF3Survey"/> A school bus at the school was pushed {{convert|75|yd|m|}} into the front entrance of the building.<ref name="NWSHuntsvilleLincoln"/> The tornado maintained EF2 strength as it moved through a small housing development and continued to cause significant damage.<ref name="LincolnEF3Survey"/>

Maintaining EF2 intensity, the storm struck another small community at 8:19&nbsp;p.m. CDT (0119&nbsp;UTC). Here, mobile homes were blown off their foundations and completely destroyed.<ref name="LincolnEF3Survey"/> Some of the homes rolled up to {{convert|50|yd|m|}} before coming to a rest.<ref name="NWSHuntsvilleLincoln"/> At 8:22&nbsp;p.m. CDT (0122&nbsp;UTC), the tornado regained EF3 strength and toppled several metal high-tension truss towers. Two nearby homes were pushed completely off of their foundations. More noticeable weakening took place thereafter, with subsequent damage not exceeding EF1 levels. The tornado crossed [[U.S. Route 64 (Tennessee)|U.S. Route 64]] around 8:25&nbsp;p.m. CDT (0125&nbsp;UTC) as it caused widespread tree damage.<ref name="LincolnEF3Survey"/> Although it had weakened, the tornado broadened to a width of {{convert|500|yd|m|abbr=on}}.<ref name="NWSHuntsvilleLincoln"/><ref name="NWSHuntsville"/> Turning north-northeast, the storm crossed into southern [[Moore County, Tennessee]] several minutes later.<ref name="LincolnEF3Survey"/> Damage was mostly confined to trees, though several barns and a few single-family homes sustained moderate roof damage. The tornado ultimately dissipated at 8:33&nbsp;p.m. CDT (0133&nbsp;UTC) roughly {{convert|3|mi|km|}} southeast of [[Lynchburg, Tennessee|Lynchburg]].<ref name="NWSHuntsvilleLincoln"/> Overall, the tornado remained on the ground for 24&nbsp;minutes and traveled {{convert|20.1|mi|km|}}, killing two people along the way.<ref name="NWSHuntsville"/>

==Flood events==
In northeastern Arkansas into southern Missouri, many areas received more than {{convert|3|in|mm|abbr=on}} of rain during the evening hours of April&nbsp;27, with a maximum of {{convert|7.6|in|mm|abbr=on}} falling in near [[Batesville, Arkansas|Batesville]].  Extensive flash flooding took place as a result and numerous roads were submerged.  A bridge along [[Arkansas Highway 25|Highway 25]] was submerged in [[Independence County, Arkansas|Independence County]] and part of the road was blocked by a mudslide near [[Desha, Arkansas|Desha]].  The [[Spring River (Arkansas)|Spring River]] rose to major flood level in [[Hardy, Arkansas|Hardy]] and [[Imboden, Arkansas|Imboden]], as did the [[Eleven Point River]] at [[Ravenden Springs, Arkansas|Ravenden Springs]].<ref name="NWSLittleRock">{{cite web|work=National Weather Service Office in Little Rock, Arkansas |publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration |date=April 29, 2014 |accessdate=April 30, 2014 |title=Tornadoes/Flooding on April 27–28, 2014 |url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov/lzk/?n=svr0414c.htm |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140502002121/http://www.srh.noaa.gov/lzk/?n=svr0414c.htm |archivedate=May 2, 2014 }}</ref> In Missouri, [[Dunklin County, Missouri|Dunklin]] and [[New Madrid County, Missouri|New Madrid]] counties were hard-hit, with residents in [[Lilbourn, Missouri|Lilbourn]] being forced to evacuate.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Ozarks First |date=April 29, 2014 |accessdate=April 30, 2014 |title=Flood Victims in SE Missouri Getting Red Cross Help |url=http://www.ozarksfirst.com/story/d/story/se-missouri-flood-victims-get-red-cross-help/38210/T0Lo5q-V6E-iQXH6olh6JQ |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140501235456/http://www.ozarksfirst.com/story/d/story/se-missouri-flood-victims-get-red-cross-help/38210/T0Lo5q-V6E-iQXH6olh6JQ |archivedate=May 1, 2014 |df= }}</ref>

Between April&nbsp;28 and 30, two rounds of severe weather along the Alabama–Tennessee border resulted in significant flash flooding. Many areas received over {{convert|4|in|mm|abbr=on}} in 48&nbsp;hours, with some recording up to {{convert|6|in|mm|abbr=on}}. One of the supercell thunderstorms that produced deadly tornadoes in northern Alabama and southern Tennessee caused near-record flooding along the Big Wills Creek in [[Fort Payne, Alabama]]. The creek crested at {{convert|13.93|ft|m|abbr=on}} early on April&nbsp;29, just {{convert|5|in|cm|abbr=on}} below its record high.<ref>{{cite web|work=National Weather Service office in Huntsville, Alabama|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|date=May 4, 2014|accessdate=May 5, 2014|title=Heavy Rainfall/Significant Flash Flooding: April 28th and 29th, 2014|url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov/hun/?n=flooding_4_29_30_2014}}</ref>

===Mobile–Pensacola (April 29–30)===
[[File:April 29-30, 2014 Pensacola rainfall.jpg|thumb|Radar estimated rainfall totals for the entire event from 8:48&nbsp;p.m. CDT on April&nbsp;28 to 9:20&nbsp;a.m. CDT on April&nbsp;30. Areas shaded in light-gray indicate precipitation totals in excess of {{convert|15|in|mm|abbr=on}}. The highlighted area denotes estimated totals of {{convert|22|to|26|in|mm|abbr=on}}.]]
During the evening hours of April&nbsp;29, torrential rains affected parts of the [[Florida Panhandle]] and nearby [[Alabama]]. The region received between {{convert|15|and|20|in|mm|abbr=on}} of rain that day and into early April&nbsp;30, with locally higher totals. Widespread [[flash flood]]ing took place in several counties, inundating homes and causing rivers to surge to near-record levels. In a 24-hour-span, roughly {{convert|22|in|mm|abbr=on}} of rain fell in [[Pensacola, Florida]],<ref name="ABC1"/> including  {{convert|5.68|in|mm|abbr=on}} an hour,<ref name="NWSMobile"/> prompting a [[flash flood emergency]]. This total accounted for roughly 33% of the city's annual rainfall.<ref name="ABC1">{{cite web|author=Melissa Nelson-Gabriel|agency=Associated Press|publisher=ABC News|date=April 30, 2014|accessdate=April 30, 2014|title=Latest Weather Wallop: Florida, Alabama Flooding|url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/wireStory/35-dead-days-tornadoes-south-midwest-23526730?singlePage=true|location=Pensacola Beach, Florida}}</ref><ref name="TP1"/> The official [[National Weather Service]] rain gauge for Pensacola, located at [[Pensacola Regional Airport]], was struck by lightning and lost power during the event. Using radar data, meteorologists estimated that the station received {{convert|15.55|in|mm|abbr=on}}, marking the greatest single-day rainfall total on record at the site (records there go back to 1879).<ref name="NWSMobile"/> Numerous residents in motor vehicles were caught in the subsequent flooding.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=News 11|date=April 29, 2014|accessdate=April 29, 2014|title=At least 2 dead in heavy Gulf Coast rains|url=http://www.11alive.com/story/news/nation/2014/04/29/gulf-coastal-areas-innundated-with-huge-rainfall/8496715/}}</ref> At least three&nbsp;hundred people were called to evacuate in the city.<ref name="ABC1"/> In the Woodbridge subdivision, a {{convert|20|ft|m|abbr=on}} retaining wall collapsed and thousands of gallons of water flooded nearby areas. The rush of water severely damaged one home and left roads covered in debris.<ref name="FirstCoast1">{{cite web|website=First Coast News|date=April 30, 2014|accessdate=April 30, 2014|title=State of emergency in Escambia Co.|url=http://www.firstcoastnews.com/story/weather/2014/04/30/state-emergency-escambia-county/8500869/}}</ref> Across [[Escambia County, Florida]], emergency crews were unable to respond to [[9-1-1]] calls as flood waters blocked off numerous roads. One person drowned in Pensacola after her car became submerged on a flooded road. In some areas, residents were forced to seek refuge in their attics as waters rose.<ref name="TP1">{{cite web|agency=Associated Press|work=The Times-Picayune|date=April 30, 2014|accessdate=April 30, 2014|title=Wicked line of storms causing 'historical flooding' in Alabama, Florida; I-10 reopened at state line|url=http://www.nola.com/weather/index.ssf/2014/04/severe_weather_causes_historic.html}}</ref> Damage in Pensacola alone was estimated in excess of $100&nbsp;million.<ref name="CNN1">{{cite web |author=Michael Pearson and Ed Payne |publisher=CNN |date=May 1, 2014 |accessdate=May 1, 2014 |title=Flood threats remain, but storm begins to fade, finally |url=http://www.cnn.com/2014/05/01/us/severe-weather/ |archivedate=May 1, 2014 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6PFjCVRqI?url=http://www.cnn.com/2014/05/01/us/severe-weather/ |deadurl=no |df=mdy }}</ref>

Across [[Okaloosa County, Florida|Okaloosa County]], {{convert|200|mi|km|abbr=on}} of paved roads and {{convert|150|mi|km|abbr=on}} of dirt roads were damaged or washed away. A total of 170&nbsp;homes were damaged by the floods, 100&nbsp;of which were in [[Fort Walton, Florida|Fort Walton]]. Significant damage took place at [[Hurlburt Field]] with several homes evacuated and {{convert|2000|ft|m|abbr=on}} of fencing in need of replacement. Twelve water pipes were also cracked or destroyed by sinkholes resulting from the flooding. At [[Eglin Air Force Base]], {{convert|22|mi|km|abbr=on}} of road was damaged of which {{convert|9|mi|km|abbr=on}} was completely decimated. At least 12&nbsp;bridges in the base were washed away or damaged. More than 350&nbsp;homes sustained severe damage in [[Santa Rosa County, Florida|Santa Rosa County]], with monetary losses estimated in excess of $4.8&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite web |publisher=NWF Daily News |date=May 3, 2014 |accessdate=May 5, 2014 |title=Counting the Cost: The great flood of 2014 by the numbers |url=http://www.nwfdailynews.com/local/storm-costs-mount-for-flood-victims-1.314696 |archivedate=May 5, 2014 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6PLUYkTDT?url=http://www.nwfdailynews.com/local/storm-costs-mount-for-flood-victims-1.314696 |deadurl=yes |df=mdy }}</ref>

In [[Gulf Shores, Alabama]], {{convert|21|in|mm|abbr=on}} of rain resulted in damage akin to hurricanes, with some residents claiming it to have been worse than [[Hurricane Ivan]] in [[2004 Atlantic hurricane season|2004]].<ref name="TP1"/> Downtown [[Mobile, Alabama|Mobile]] was inundated and authorities used [[Reverse 911|reverse 9-1-1]] to warn residents of rising waters along the [[Fish River (Alabama)|Fish River]].<ref name="NBC1"/> The river ultimately crested at a record height of {{convert|23.18|ft|m|abbr=on}} surpassing the previous peak of {{convert|22.78|ft|m|abbr=on}} set during [[Hurricane Danny (1997)|Hurricane Danny]] in July 1997.<ref name="NWSMobile">{{cite web|work=National Weather Service office in Mobile, Alabama|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|date=May 1, 2014|accessdate=May 1, 2014|title=North Central Gulf Coast Historic Flash Flood Event – 29–30 April 2014|url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov/mob/?n=flashflood_04292014}}</ref> At least fifty people required rescue from their cars in the city.<ref name="NBC1">{{cite web|author1=Alastair Jamieson |author2=M. Alex Johnson |author3=Erin McClam |publisher=NBC News|date=April 30, 2014|accessdate=April 30, 2014|title='Life-Threatening' Flooding Submerges Pensacola, Florida|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/storyline/deadly-tornado-outbreak/life-threatening-flooding-submerges-pensacola-florida-n93201}}</ref> [[Baldwin County, Alabama]] emergency management director Mitchell Sims called the flooding "historical."<ref name="TP1"/>

The extreme rainfall in Pensacola had a recurrence period of 1-in-100 to 1-in-200 years. The most notable aspect of the rainfall was the {{convert|5.68|in|mm|abbr=on}} that fell in a single hour, which had a return frequency of 1-in-200 to 1-in-500 years. The event in Mobile, Alabama was slightly less significant, having a return period of 1-in-25 years.<ref name="NWSMobile"/>

Around 11:00&nbsp;p.m. CDT on April&nbsp;30, a [[natural gas]] explosion occurred at the Escambia County Central Booking and Detention Center, killing at least 2&nbsp;people and injuring 185&nbsp;others. The cause of the explosion is currently unknown, however, flooding from the storm had damaged the building earlier that day.<ref>{{cite web|author=T. S. Strickland|work=Pensacola News Journal|via=USA Today|date=May 1, 2014|accessdate=May 1, 2014|title=3 still hospitalized after jail explosion|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2014/05/01/florida-jail-explosion/8550957/}}</ref>

===Mid-Atlantic states (April 29 – May 1)===
As the storm complex slowly moved eastward, much of the Eastern United States was affected by steady, heavy rain, bringing the worst flooding in the region since [[Hurricane Irene]]. Particularly intense rains fell around the [[Washington metropolitan area|Washington metro]] and surrounding areas as more than a month worth of rain fell in 24&nbsp;hours.<ref name="NWSBaltimore"/><ref name="WP3">{{cite web|author=Jason Samenow|work=The Washington Post|date=May 1, 2014|accessdate=May 1, 2014|title=Record-setting rainfall: 3–7 inches fall across D.C. area|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/capital-weather-gang/wp/2014/05/01/rainfall-was-record-setting-3-7-inches-fall-across-d-c-area/?tid=pm_local_pop}}</ref> The [[Aberdeen Proving Ground]] received the highest total of {{convert|7.57|in|mm|abbr=on}} while many other areas reported more than {{convert|6|in|mm|abbr=on}}. In Washington, D.C. proper, measurements peaked at {{convert|4.74|in|mm|abbr=on}}.<ref name="NWSBaltimore"/> At [[Washington Dulles International Airport]], {{convert|3.99|in|mm|abbr=on}} fell on April&nbsp;30, setting a record for the day and the month of April.<ref name="WP3"/> Up to {{convert|6.5|in|mm|abbr=on}} fell in [[Baltimore, Maryland]].<ref name="NWSBaltimore">{{cite web |work=National Weather Service Office in Baltimore, Maryland/Washington, D.C. |publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration |date=May 1, 2014 |accessdate=May 1, 2014 |title=Public Information Statement: Storm Total Rainfall |url=https://nwschat.weather.gov/p.php?pid=201405011633-KLWX-NOUS41-PNSLWX |archivedate=May 1, 2014 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6PFg6vFqR?url=https://nwschat.weather.gov/p.php?pid=201405011633-KLWX-NOUS41-PNSLWX |deadurl=no |df=mdy }}</ref> Numerous roads around the region were temporarily closed due to flooding.<ref name="WP1"/>

The [[Rocky Gorge Reservoir]] in [[Maryland]] swelled above its banks and threatened to collapse as water began seeping through joints in the Duckett Dam, eroding soil. In order to alleviate the risk of this, officials conducted a controlled release of the Dam and evacuated 200&nbsp;nearby residents. Seven gates were opened late on April&nbsp;30 to lower water levels while simultaneously flooding parts of [[Laurel, Maryland|Laurel]]. An inspection the following morning determined that the dam sustained no damage. The nearby [[Triadelphia Reservoir]] also had water released through the Brighton Dam. In [[Hyattsville, Maryland|Hyattsville]], one family had to evacuate due to flooding. Two [[Washington Suburban Sanitary Commission]] waste water systems overflowed in [[Prince George's County, Maryland|Prince George's County]].<ref name="WP1">{{cite web|author1=Dana Hedgpeth |author2=Jason Samenow |author3=Lynh Bui |work=The Washington Post |date=May 1, 2014 |accessdate=May 1, 2014 |title=As showers abate, D.C. area starts to dry out, recover from flooding |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/flooding-problems-trouble-dc-region-after-heavy-rainfalls/2014/05/01/f1f53528-d113-11e3-a6b1-45c4dffb85a6_story.html?noredirect=on}}{{dead link|date=May 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> In the [[Charles Village, Baltimore|Charles Village]] neighborhood of Baltimore, a street collapsed along an embankment above a [[CSX Transportation|CSX]] rail line, covering the tracks and taking several cars with it. No buildings were damaged by the collapse but residents in nearby homes were ordered to evacuate until inspections determined if it was safe to stay there.<ref name="WP2">{{cite web|author= Peter Hermann|work=The Washington Post|date=April 30, 2014|accessdate=May 1, 2014|title=Street collapses in Baltimore, washing away cars|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/street-collapses-in-baltimore-washing-away-cars/2014/04/30/89f6dcfa-d0b0-11e3-a6b1-45c4dffb85a6_story.html}}</ref>

The entirety of the [[Delaware River]]'s watershed experienced flooding of varying degrees due to the storm. The [[Brandywine Creek (Christina River)|Brandywine Creek]] in [[Delaware]] rose to {{convert|4|ft|m|abbr=on}} above flood-stage, inundating nearby areas and closing numerous roads. The river also flowed at 14.3&nbsp;billion gallons per day near [[Chadds Ford, Pennsylvania]], the third-highest on record. Downstream, a gauge near [[Brandywine Park]] broke well-before peak flows reached the area. Several families along the river were evacuated due to rising waters. The [[White Clay Creek]], a tributary to the Brandywine Creek, reached its fourth-highest flow on record at 9.44&nbsp;billion gallons per day. Additionally, the [[Red Clay Creek]] crested at its sixth-highest level on record. Throughout Delaware, 81&nbsp;road accidents related to the rain took place, with 11&nbsp;resulting in injuries.<ref>{{cite web|author1=Jeff Montgomery |author2=Yann Ranaivo |publisher=Delaware Online|date=April 30, 2014|accessdate=May 1, 2014|title=Damage assessed as Brandywine slowly recedes|url=http://www.delawareonline.com/story/weather/2014/04/30/more-rain-strong-thunderstorms-in-forecast-for-delaware/8503969/}}</ref>

A landslide in [[Yonkers]], [[New York (state)|New York]], south of the [[Glenwood (Metro-North station)|Glenwood]] station, interfered with [[Metro-North]]'s [[Hudson Line (Metro-North)|Hudson Line]], blocking two tracks and causing delays.<ref>{{cite web|publisher = The Wall Street Journal|date=May 1, 2014|accessdate=May 3, 2014|title=Metro-North delays expected due to mudslide|url=https://online.wsj.com/article/APf784983282f348058912de69da33ee96.html}}</ref>

==Aftermath==
Prior to the arrival of severe storms, a [[state of emergency]] was declared for Alabama, Florida, Georgia, and Tennessee on April&nbsp;28.<ref name="ALSoE"/><ref>{{cite web|author=Jacques Rozier|publisher=WMAZ|date=April 28, 2014|accessdate=April 30, 2014|title=State of Emergency declared in Georgia|url=http://www.13wmaz.com/story/news/2014/04/28/state-of-emergency-georgia/8444219/}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|publisher=WRCB|date=April 28, 2014|accessdate=April 30, 2014|title=TEMA activates state of emergency|url=http://www.wrcbtv.com/story/25369172/tema-activates-state-of-emergency}}</ref> In Alabama, 100&nbsp;National Guard troops were placed on standby to assist communities.<ref name="ALSoE">{{cite web|website=Dothan First |date=April 28, 2014 |accessdate=April 30, 2014 |title=Governor Bentley Declares State of Emergency As Severe Weather Impacts Alabama |url=http://www.dothanfirst.com/story/d/story/governor-bentley-declares-state-of-emergency-as-se/17461/hJLqsPnGCUeXDB6c-yseTQ |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140502004311/http://www.dothanfirst.com/story/d/story/governor-bentley-declares-state-of-emergency-as-se/17461/hJLqsPnGCUeXDB6c-yseTQ |archivedate=May 2, 2014 |df= }}</ref>  Following destructive tornadoes later that day, a state of emergency was also declared for Mississippi.  State Medical Assistance Teams were deployed to Tupelo and Winston County while a resupply truck was sent to Winston County.  Additionally, a public shelter was opened in Lee County.<ref>{{cite web|website=The Clarion-Ledger|date=April 28, 2014|accessdate=April 30, 2014|title=State of emergency declared as tornadoes rip Miss.|url=http://www.clarionledger.com/story/news/local/2014/04/28/governor-declares-state-of-emergency/8415803/}}</ref> [[Ottawa County, Oklahoma]] was later placed under a state of emergency as well.<ref>{{cite web|agency=Associated Press|publisher=KBTX|date=April 28, 2014|accessdate=April 30, 2014|title=State of Emergency Declared for Ottawa County, Oklahoma|url=http://www.kbtx.com/home/headlines/State-of-Emergency-Declared-for-Ottawa-County-Oklahoma-257012611.html}}</ref>

On April&nbsp;29, [[Faulkner County, Arkansas]], was declared a federal disaster area by President [[Barack Obama]].  This allowed residents to receive federal aid and low-cost loans to cover uninsured losses.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Federal Emergency Management Agency|date=April 29, 2014|accessdate=April 30, 2014|title=President Declares Disaster for Arkansas|url=http://www.fema.gov/news-release/2014/04/29/president-declares-disaster-arkansas|location=Washington, D.C.}}</ref>

In the wake of the severe flooding in Florida, [[List of Governors of Florida|Governor]] [[Rick Scott]] declared a state of emergency for 26&nbsp;counties.  The [[Florida National Guard]], equipped with high-water rescue vehicles, was deployed to the Panhandle region early on April&nbsp;30.  Additionally, the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission provided thirty-one road vehicles and thirteen boats to assist.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Government of Florida|date=April 30, 2014|accessdate=April 30, 2014|title=Gov. Rick Scott Provides Update on Storm Response Efforts|url=http://www.flgov.com/2014/04/30/gov-rick-scott-provides-update-on-storm-response-efforts/}}</ref>  A local state of emergency was also declared in Escambia County.  Throughout the county, all schools and businesses were closed and only essential personnel were to report to work.  Emergency officials urged all residents to stay home and not call 9-1-1 unless they had a life-threatening emergency.  A [[American Red Cross|Red Cross]] shelter was opened in Pensacola to house displaced residents.<ref name="FirstCoast1"/> Similarly, local emergencies were raised in [[Walton County, Florida|Walton]] and [[Washington County, Florida|Washington]] counties as well as the cities of [[Crestview, Florida|Crestview]] and [[Destin, Florida|Destin]].<ref>{{cite web|publisher=WMBB|date=April 30, 2014|accessdate=April 30, 2014|title=Local State of Emergency Declarations|url=http://www.wmbb.com/story/25381709/local-state-of-emergency-declarations}}</ref>

On April&nbsp;30, freight rail on the [[CSX]] line north from [[Baltimore]] was interrupted, perhaps for days, when an unstable retaining wall in the [[Charles Village]] section of the city collapsed, sending several automobiles off the road into the railway gully.<ref name="CSX"/>

